          },
          {
            "type": "bullets",
            "items": [
              "The capability gap between frontier and open-source models is still large",
              "For research workflows, you need the best reasoning, not just code generation",
              "The cost is real, but **relative to their power**, it is surprisingly accessible"
            ],
            "bulletStyle": "disc",
            "style": { "fontSize": "large" },
            "animation": { "fragment": true, "type": "fade", "index": 1 },
            "position": { "area": "content", "order": 1 }
          },
          {
            "type": "callout",
            "calloutType": "important",
            "title": "The Paradox",
            "content": "I use closed-source tools to create **more open science**. The AI helps me publish open datasets, open-source plugins, and reproducible workflows faster than I ever could alone.",
            "animation": { "fragment": true, "type": "slide-up", "index": 2 },
            "position": { "area": "content", "order": 2 }
          }
        ],
        "speakerNotes": "I know some of you might wonder: why closed-source AI for open science? The answer: these tools are massively powerful, and I use that power to produce more open-source code, more open datasets, more transparent research. The tool being closed-source doesn't make the output closed."
