        "transition": "slide",
        "elements": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "content": "## The Three States of Git",
            "style": { "fontSize": "xl" },
            "position": { "area": "header" }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "content": "### Working Directory &nbsp; --`git add`--> &nbsp; Staging Area &nbsp; --`git commit`--> &nbsp; Repository &nbsp; --`git push`--> &nbsp; GitHub",
            "style": {
              "fontSize": "medium",
              "alignment": "center",
              "color": "#2563EB",
              "fontWeight": "bold"
            },
            "position": { "area": "content" }
          },
          {
            "type": "bullets",
            "items": [
              "**Working directory** -- your files as you see them right now",
              "**Staging area** -- changes you've selected for the next snapshot",
              "**Repository** -- the permanent history of all snapshots"
            ],
            "bulletStyle": "disc",
            "style": { "fontSize": "large" },
            "animation": { "fragment": true, "type": "fade" },
            "position": { "area": "content", "order": 1 }
          },
          {
            "type": "callout",
            "calloutType": "tip",
            "content": "Think of it like photography: you **arrange** the scene (staging), then **take the photo** (commit). The photo album (repository) keeps every shot forever.",
            "animation": { "fragment": true, "type": "slide-up" },
            "position": { "area": "footer" }
          }
        ],
        "speakerNotes": "Git has three states. Your working directory is what you see. The staging area is where you select what goes into the next snapshot. The repository is the permanent history. Think of it like photography: arrange the scene, take the photo, and the album keeps every shot forever."
      },
      {
        "id": "git-commands",
        "layout": "single-column",
        "transition": "slide",
        "elements": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "content": "## Essential Git Commands",
            "style": { "fontSize": "xl" },
            "position": { "area": "header" }
          },
          {
            "type": "code",
            "code": "# Create a new repository\ngit init my-research-project\ncd my-research-project\n\n# Check what's changed\ngit status\n\n# Stage files for commit\ngit add analysis.py\n\n# Take the snapshot\ngit commit -m \"feat: add initial analysis script\"\n\n# View history\ngit log --oneline",
            "language": "bash",
            "caption": "The daily workflow",
            "animation": { "fragment": true, "type": "fade", "index": 0 },
            "position": { "area": "content" }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "content": "**That's it.** `status`, `add`, `commit`, `log`. Four commands for daily use.",
            "style": {
              "fontSize": "large",
              "alignment": "center",
              "color": "#059669",
              "fontWeight": "bold"
            },
            "animation": { "fragment": true, "type": "slide-up", "index": 1 },
            "position": { "area": "footer" }
          }
        ],
        "speakerNotes": "Here are the commands you'll use every day. git init creates the repo. git status shows what changed. git add selects files. git commit takes the snapshot. git log shows history. That's the core loop."
      },
      {
        "id": "push-pull",
        "layout": "single-column",
        "transition": "slide",
        "elements": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "content": "## Connecting to GitHub",
            "style": { "fontSize": "xl" },
            "position": { "area": "header" }
          },
          {
            "type": "code",
            "code": "# Push your local work to GitHub\ngit push origin main\n\n# Get updates from GitHub\ngit pull origin main\n\n# Clone someone else's project\ngit clone https://github.com/user/repo.git",
            "language": "bash",
            "caption": "Syncing local and remote",
            "animation": { "fragment": true, "type": "fade", "index": 0 },
            "position": { "area": "content" }
          },
          {
            "type": "callout",
            "calloutType": "info",
            "title": "Why GitHub?",
            "content": "GitHub is your **backup**, your **portfolio**, and your **collaboration platform**. It is also where Claude Code creates pull requests and tracks issues.",
            "animation": { "fragment": true, "type": "slide-up", "index": 1 },
            "position": { "area": "content", "order": 1 }
          }
        ],
        "speakerNotes": "GitHub is the remote copy of your repository. Push sends your commits up, pull brings updates down, clone copies an existing project. GitHub is where AI agents will create PRs, track issues, and collaborate with you."
      },
